# Claude Code as a GitHub App: Setup & Auth

Goal: Claude Code authenticates to GitHub as a dedicated GitHub App identity, not as you. Commits, pushes, PRs, and issue comments are attributed to the App. Your personal `~/.gitconfig` is left alone.

This doc covers a GitHub Teams org. Same procedure works on Free/Pro/Enterprise; only the org-level UI paths differ slightly.

---

## 1. Register the GitHub App

In the org that owns the repos:

**Org settings → Developer settings → GitHub Apps → New GitHub App**

Fill in:

- **Name**: e.g. `claude-bot` (must be globally unique across GitHub; pick something org-scoped if needed, like `example-claude-app`)
- **Homepage URL**: anything; your org URL is fine
- **Webhook**: uncheck **Active** — you don't need webhooks for local Claude Code usage
- **Repository permissions** (starter set):
  - Contents: **Read & write**
  - Pull requests: **Read & write**
  - Issues: **Read & write**
  - Metadata: **Read** (auto-selected)
  - Checks: **Read** (lets Claude see CI status)
  - Workflows: **Read & write** *only if* you want Claude to modify files under `.github/workflows/`
- **Where can this GitHub App be installed?**: **Only on this account**

Create the App.

After creation, on the App's settings page note:

- **App ID** (numeric, top of the page)
- **Slug** (from the URL: `https://github.com/organizations/<org>/settings/apps/<slug>`)

Then:

- **Generate a private key** → downloads a `.pem` file. Store it somewhere safe; you cannot re-download it.
- Optionally rotate/regenerate later from this same page.

---

## 2. Install the App on your repos

Still on the App's settings page: **Install App** (left nav) → choose your org → **Only select repositories** → pick the repos Claude should work on.

After install, note the **Installation ID**. Easiest way: the install URL ends with `/installations/<id>`. Or query it later with the API.

---

## 3. Identify the App's bot identity

GitHub assigns every App a synthetic user with this email format:

```
<APP_ID>+<SLUG>[bot]@users.noreply.github.com
```

Example: App ID `1234567`, slug `claude-bot` →

```
1234567+claude-bot[bot]@users.noreply.github.com
```

**This exact format is what makes GitHub attribute commits to the bot account with the `[bot]` badge.** Any other email and GitHub will just show the literal string.

The matching display name convention is `claude-bot[bot]`.

---

## 4. Local setup

### 4.1 Store credentials

```bash
mkdir -p ~/.config/claude-github-app
chmod 700 ~/.config/claude-github-app
mv ~/Downloads/claude-bot.*.private-key.pem ~/.config/claude-github-app/private-key.pem
chmod 600 ~/.config/claude-github-app/private-key.pem
```

Create `~/.config/claude-github-app/config`:

```bash
APP_ID=1234567
INSTALLATION_ID=98765432
APP_SLUG=claude-bot
BOT_NAME="claude-bot[bot]"
BOT_EMAIL="1234567+claude-bot[bot]@users.noreply.github.com"
PRIVATE_KEY=~/.config/claude-github-app/private-key.pem
```

```bash
chmod 600 ~/.config/claude-github-app/config
```

(macOS Keychain is an option for the PEM, but file perms + FileVault is fine for a single-user dev machine.)

### 4.2 Token-minting script

Installation tokens last ≤1 hour. This script mints a fresh one (cached on disk until ~5 min before expiry) and prints it to stdout.

`~/.config/claude-github-app/get-token.sh`:

```bash
#!/usr/bin/env bash
set -euo pipefail

CONFIG_DIR="$HOME/.config/claude-github-app"
CACHE_FILE="$CONFIG_DIR/.token-cache"
# shellcheck source=/dev/null
source "$CONFIG_DIR/config"

# Reuse cached token if it has >5 min left
if [[ -f "$CACHE_FILE" ]]; then
  expires_at=$(jq -r .expires_at_epoch "$CACHE_FILE" 2>/dev/null || echo 0)
  now=$(date +%s)
  if (( expires_at - now > 300 )); then
    jq -r .token "$CACHE_FILE"
    exit 0
  fi
fi

# Build JWT (RS256) signed with the App's private key
header=$(printf '{"alg":"RS256","typ":"JWT"}' | base64 | tr -d '=' | tr '/+' '_-')
now=$(date +%s)
payload=$(printf '{"iat":%d,"exp":%d,"iss":"%s"}' $((now-60)) $((now+540)) "$APP_ID" \
  | base64 | tr -d '=' | tr '/+' '_-')
sig=$(printf '%s.%s' "$header" "$payload" \
  | openssl dgst -sha256 -sign "$PRIVATE_KEY" \
  | base64 | tr -d '=' | tr '/+' '_-' | tr -d '\n')
jwt="$header.$payload.$sig"

# Exchange JWT for installation token
resp=$(curl -sS -X POST \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $jwt" \
  -H "Accept: application/vnd.github+json" \
  -H "X-GitHub-Api-Version: 2022-11-28" \
  "https://api.github.com/app/installations/$INSTALLATION_ID/access_tokens")

token=$(echo "$resp" | jq -r .token)
expires_at=$(echo "$resp" | jq -r .expires_at)

if [[ "$token" == "null" || -z "$token" ]]; then
  echo "Failed to mint installation token: $resp" >&2
  exit 1
fi

expires_at_epoch=$(date -j -f "%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ" "$expires_at" +%s 2>/dev/null \
  || date -d "$expires_at" +%s)

jq -n --arg t "$token" --arg ea "$expires_at" --argjson eae "$expires_at_epoch" \
  '{token:$t, expires_at:$ea, expires_at_epoch:$eae}' > "$CACHE_FILE"
chmod 600 "$CACHE_FILE"

echo "$token"
```

```bash
chmod 700 ~/.config/claude-github-app/get-token.sh
```

Test it:

```bash
~/.config/claude-github-app/get-token.sh
# → ghs_xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx
```

### 4.3 Git credential helper

Tell git to use the App token as the password for HTTPS GitHub URLs.

`~/.config/claude-github-app/credential-helper.sh`:

```bash
#!/usr/bin/env bash
# git invokes this with `get` and reads username=/password= from stdout
if [[ "${1:-}" == "get" ]]; then
  echo "username=x-access-token"
  echo "password=$(~/.config/claude-github-app/get-token.sh)"
fi
```

```bash
chmod 700 ~/.config/claude-github-app/credential-helper.sh
```

You have two choices for wiring it in:

- **Per-repo (recommended for "trying it on my own stuff")** — see §5.
- **Globally for all GitHub HTTPS** — only if you want *all* your local git operations against GitHub to go through the App. Probably not what you want, because it'd hijack your personal repos too. Skip unless you're sure.

---

## 5. Per-repo git config (the override)

Inside each repo where Claude operates:

```bash
cd /path/to/repo

# Source the bot identity
source ~/.config/claude-github-app/config

# Override author/committer locally — does NOT touch ~/.gitconfig
git config --local user.name  "$BOT_NAME"
git config --local user.email "$BOT_EMAIL"

# Wire the credential helper for this repo only
# The leading `!` makes git treat the value as a shell command
git config --local credential.helper "!$HOME/.config/claude-github-app/credential-helper.sh"

# Make sure the remote is HTTPS, not SSH (SSH would bypass the helper)
git remote set-url origin "https://github.com/<org>/<repo>.git"
```

Verify:

```bash
git config --local --get-regexp '^(user|credential|remote\.origin\.url)\.'
```

You should see the bot name/email, the helper, and an `https://` origin. Your global `user.name`/`user.email` are untouched and still apply to every other repo.

### 5.1 One-shot setup script

Drop this in `~/.config/claude-github-app/init-repo.sh` to apply the above to any repo:

```bash
#!/usr/bin/env bash
set -euo pipefail
source ~/.config/claude-github-app/config

if ! git rev-parse --git-dir >/dev/null 2>&1; then
  echo "Not a git repo: $(pwd)" >&2
  exit 1
fi

git config --local user.name  "$BOT_NAME"
git config --local user.email "$BOT_EMAIL"
git config --local credential.helper "!$HOME/.config/claude-github-app/credential-helper.sh"

origin=$(git remote get-url origin 2>/dev/null || true)
if [[ "$origin" == git@github.com:* ]]; then
  https_url="https://github.com/${origin#git@github.com:}"
  https_url="${https_url%.git}.git"
  git remote set-url origin "$https_url"
  echo "Switched origin to HTTPS: $https_url"
fi

echo "Repo configured for $BOT_NAME"
```

```bash
chmod 700 ~/.config/claude-github-app/init-repo.sh
```

Then per repo: `cd repo && ~/.config/claude-github-app/init-repo.sh`.

